  <Fragment slot="residual-market">
    <p>Florida Citizens Property Insurance Corporation is the state-chartered insurer of last resort. It is not a private company and not a state agency. It operates as a nonprofit government entity funded by premiums, investment income, and a legal authority to levy assessments on all Florida insurance policyholders if it runs short of funds.</p>
    <p><strong>What Citizens covers:</strong> Dwelling, other structures, personal property, loss of use, personal liability, and medical payments. It is a more complete product than California's FAIR Plan.</p>
    <p><strong>Wind deductible:</strong> Citizens applies a wind deductible separate from the standard deductible — typically 2 to 5 percent of the dwelling coverage amount in coastal zones. On a $350,000 home, a 2 percent deductible means $7,000 out of pocket before wind coverage begins.</p>
    <p><strong>Flood:</strong> Not covered. A separate NFIP or private flood policy is required. In Florida, flood coverage is often as important as wind coverage.</p>
    <p><strong>Assessment risk:</strong> If Citizens' claims exceed its resources, it can levy surcharges on all Florida insurance policyholders — including auto, commercial, and others who do not hold Citizens policies. This is called the "hurricane tax." The last emergency assessment was issued after the 2004–2005 hurricane seasons.</p>
    <p><strong>How to apply:</strong> Through any licensed Florida insurance agent. You cannot apply directly. Citizens is available only if your premium from a private admitted carrier is more than 20 percent above Citizens' rate.</p>
  </Fragment>

